verbatim_cdownload_content: #BrandPartner When I came out one of the things my parents struggled with was this dream they had of me starting a family. I explained that just because I was gay (and now non-binary) doesn't mean that I don't still want a family. I'm such a loving, obsessive virgo mom that a partner and kids (furry or human) have to be in my life. Every family is unique, and families in the LGBTQ community are no exception. Whether chosen, biological or adopted, our families are sources of unconditional love and joy in a sometimes tumultuous world. Mine (pictured above) is made up of my loving boyfriend logansamuelson and my cat Chicken. I'm proud to support Listerine and the #CareWithPride initiative as they raise money for LGBTQ non-profits like The Family Equality Council. FamilyEquality advocates on behalf of LGBTQ families, envisioning a world "in which every LGBTQ person has the right and the opportunity to form and sustain a loving family, regardless of sexual orientation, gender identity, race, religion, national origin, geography, socioeconomic status, disability, or the intersection of those characteristics." Diverse families create diverse stewards of our future, and to support that is priceless.

verbatim_cdownload_content:
Brushing cannot remove all the plaque located in places the toothbrush can't reach, like between the teeth and under the gums.

Flossing is important because it reaches these areas to reduce the amount of bacteria and plaque in the mouth â?? resulting in a healthier mouth.

But, flossing can be tricky for kids and parents, and all the options can be confusing. Letâ??s review how to make flossing easier!

______________________________________
.
â­?ï? WHEN SHOULD MY CHILD START FLOSSING?
Flossing should start when your child has 2 teeth that touch. Often times, this is when the primary molars erupt, around ages 2 to 3.
.
ð?· HOW OFTEN SHOULD MY CHILD FLOSS?
Once a day, for about 2 to 3 minutes.
.
ð??§ð??» SHOULD I FLOSS FOR MY CHILD?
Until your child is 8 to 10 years old and develops their manual dexterity, you will need to help your child floss.
.
______________________________________

FLOSSING TIPS:
.
1ï?â?£ Floss gently in between your child's teeth; do not snap it in. It is important to floss correctly so that you don't damage your child's teeth or gums.
.
2ï?â?£ Healthy habits start early, so even if your child's teeth donâ??t touch, you can introduce the concept of flossing after you have a good brushing routine.
.
3ï?â?£ Teach your child that flossing cleans the sides of the teeth. Without flossing, the teeth are only half clean.
.
4ï?â?£ Don't worry if your child's gums bleed at first. Your child may also initially complain that flossing is uncomfortable. The gums will become healthier as flossing becomes a daily habit, and these symptoms will fade.
.
5ï?â?£ Be patient and flexible, try finding what works best for your child to make flossing fun!

______________________________________

FLOSS OPTIONS FOR CHILDREN:
.
â?«ï?TRADITIONAL FLOSS: comes in different varieties: flavored & unflavored, waxed & non-waxed, and nylon & monofilament.
.
â?«ï?FLOSS HOLDERS: can be easier to use, but more expensive than regular floss.
.
â?«ï?WATER-PIK: great for cleaning areas the toothbrush can't reach, but should not be used as a replacement for flossing.

______________________________________

When did your child start flossing?
What kind do they use?

verbatim_cdownload_content:
There is no one right answer to this question. Not all oral washes are created equal, the American Dental Association classifies mouth rinses into three categories: plaque/gingivitis control, fluoride mouthrinse, and plaque disclosing rinses. In order to find the right rinse for yourself you must first identify what you need it for. Keep reading to see the top 2 mouthwashes we recommend for our patients.

Listerine is one of the best mouthwashes for periodontal disease and gingivitis.  It is extremely effective in killing bacteria above the gumline as well as reducing sticky plaque film. You want to elect alcohol free listerine as alcohol rinses can cause dry mouth especially if used on a daily basis.

ACT is one of the best mouthiness for preventing cavities. The active ingredient in this mouthwash is fluoride which helps strengthen enamel, and contains remineralization properties.

Ask your doctor about which mouthwash is best for you to use. And remember, mouth rinses do not replace brushing and flossing, they are used as an adjunctive tool.

DISCLAIMER: there are many others we recommend based on patient needs. However, these two have to be the most commonly recommended in our practice. There has been no paid sponsorship by either brand.

BABY TEETH MATTER!
They need brushed every day, 2x a day, and need flossed if they are touching each other. Baby teeth are more susceptible to decay, and decay that goes on too long can be painful, cause abscess or affect the adult teeth! 
They donâ??t just fall out anyways - some of those teeth are in there until they are preteens. If they have to be pulled out too soon that means irregular eruption (Hello Braces!) or appliances to maintain the space.
I donâ??t care how independent your little genius is, if they canâ??t tie their shoes or write a sentence, they canâ??t brush without help. Even if they can brush on their own-check that they are doing it and doing it well! That kid is yours for 18 years, thatâ??s a huge amount of time to teach good hygiene habits. 
Tips:
- There are toothbrushes for all ages - start them young (even just brushing gums) so they get used to it
- Electric toothbrushes are the best investment and there are some pretty cool ones that make brushing fun! oralb philipssonicare - Do it together - why would they do it if you arenâ??t? Monkey see, monkey do. ð??µ

.

PRODUCT EMPTIES AKA FUTURE TRASH(1/2): May-June. Total of 30 products used up; both in sample and full sizes. I will run through and review some of these items and answer, â??would I buy?â??
The josiemarancosmetics Whipped Argan Oil Body Butter I was excited to try when I picked it up as a sample from sephora. So excited that I grabbed two of them. Each sample contained an â??unscentedâ?? and a â??honeysuckle vanillaâ?? variety. The lotion felt a greasy, took a little while for my skin to soak up. Both smelled strongly bitter. I believe itâ??s the aloe juice, which is 2nd on the ingredients list. I know Iâ??m very particular about scents, so it might not bother you. I will not buy in a full size.
The halobeauty Kiwi Seed Booster is the first bottle I have completed. I am contemplating picking up some more to get a better feel for the product. So far, the results are inconclusive because I am in the midst of changing my skin care products. I donâ??t want the testing of new products to interfere with whether I like or dislike this product for me.
The sephora cleansing wipes are not for me. The exfoliating wipes are too rough for my sensitive skin and both wipes felt stripping. In a previous empties I talked about taking makeup wipes out of my routines to see if the quality of my skin improves. So far, so good. I switched them out for an oil cleanser to remove makeup. 
The urbandecaycosmetics â??Brow Endowedâ?? primer and color duo samples in â??Taupeâ?? and â??Brunette Bettyâ?? are an absolute disappointment. I was in the market for a new brow product. First impressionâ??the product laid funky. I finessed it a bit and left my house. After some wear timeâ??a couple of hours inâ??my eyebrows looked so awful. The makeup was breaking up throughout my eyebrows. Will not be picking up the product in a full size.
bumbleandbumble â??Hairdresserâ??s Invisible Oilâ?? is nothing special. I used it as an overnight oil treatment. Would not purchase.
listerine mint flossâ??your reminder to floss daily ;) Iâ??ll buy floss again. Definitely like these as opposed to the glide ones. 
armandhammer is a holy grail.

Gay twitter has torn apart pride campaigns, criticizing them for being lazy, opportunistic, overly centered on the pride flag, or insensitive. Brands are platforms, and the decision to use them to affect change or raise money for LGBTQIA+ non-profits is real visibility and impact that we should support. For example, Listerine and the #CareWithPride initiative have raised over $1 million for LGBTQIA+ non-profits like PFLAG, The Trevor Project, and The Family Equality Council. So...the solution works to a degree.  Here's my experience

1. My foot basin is really deep so i "eye balled" adjusting the solution after seeing that the ingredients weren't going to be deep enough. 
2. While it says any listerine I wonder if the original listerine  combined with apple_cider_vinegar_ng would have a stronger concentration

3. I sat for 15m, but depending on your level of need it could be shorter or longer

4. I used my battery operated pumice stone, I didn't use a simple cloth to "wipe the dead skin away"

5. Also in the interest of science I used the pumice stone my left foot while it was wet. I let my right foot dry for an hour and then I used my pumice  stone on my right foot. Foot became softer when it was wet so I would say whether using a cloth or a pumice stone you may see different result if you let your feet get totally dry 
6. My battery operated pumice stone is made by  Amope Pedi

Can we talk about waste in dentistry for a minute? Why does toothpaste have to come in boxes? Itâ??s already in a sealed plastic bottle (eventual waste) and then is sold in a box that gets instantly thrown away (immediate waste). Just because itâ??s the way something has always been sold and it looks pretty doesnâ??t mean that itâ??s the way it should be sold. What if toothpaste looked just like this sitting on the shelf? What if your bottle had a little dent or wrinkle from shipping? Does that even matter if we know we are able to create less needless waste? .
.
.
What do we have to do in America to make these changes? Toothpaste is sold just like this in Iceland, no individual boxes needed. Yeah the boxes look nice, but for what? We have so much waste in dentistry from plastic barriers and single use infection control items which are important to protect our patients during their office visits, but can we as an industry try and cut down on the waste that isnâ??t necessary? verbatim_cdownload_content:
Car: 1992 BMW 318iS Super Touring Car (Chassis No. VLM E36-001)

This particular 318iS was built by Vic Lee Motorsport for the 1992 BTCC season, to be raced by Tim Harvey. The car would play a role in one of the most controversial and exciting touring car finishes of all time. 3 drivers were fighting for the championship at the close of the 1992 BTCC season; Vauxhall's John Cleland, Toyota's Will Hoy, and our protagonist in this instance, Tim Harvey. At the start of the race, Harvey's teammate Steve Soper would be pitched into a spin, damaging his BMW. Soper would fight his way back through the field, eventually muscling past Cleland while he was fighting with Harvey for 4th place and the championship. Cleland was not best pleased by this, and after Soper let Harvey past to further improve his championship likelihood, Cleland dive bombed Soper, passing the BMW on two wheels. Soper however, decided to take to the grass and hit Cleland, ending both of their races and making Harvey the resulting BTCC champion of 1992. The car now resides in New Zealand, driven by Warren Good in the Archibalds' Historic Touring Cars series.

verbatim_cdownload_content:
We hope you are all well and staying safe in these unprecedented times.  We care about each of you and want to provide some guidance while you're staying home on how to stay on top of your oral health. "If I'm missing my checkup, should I do anything differently?"
It's never been more important to do the best job possible to maintain your oral health.
Since many of us will have extra time on our hands, make sure you brush and floss at least twice a day for two minutes. If you feel like you want to take extra steps to protect your hygiene during this time, here are a few ideas:
1) Use a powered toothbrush, such as the Sonicare
2) Use an irrigation device, such as the waterpik 
3) Use your favorite mouthwash, such as listerine Total or closysoralcare 
4) Use a mild, fluoridated toothpaste, such as Sensodyne
4) Floss - if you don't currently floss, it's a great opportunity to start!

You have the extra time and once you're in the habit, you'll like the extra clean feeling while also strengthening your gums!

During this time that we're all asked to stay home, you can be comfortable that your dental health will be fine by maintaining basic home hygiene. During this time, you will notice that there may be many things different in the dental office. If you're still confused or unclear as to whether you need to be seen in our office, email us or call us.

Stay home, stay safe, and know that we are here for you.

Mouthwash was my drink of choice.
.
It's crazy to even type this now, I cringe at the thought of it.
.
Someone posted in my groups of how "some alcoholics go to this extreme for several reasons".
.
That was me. 8 years ago. You might not have noticed from my demeanor at the time. I was really good at hiding it. Waylon was the only one who saw my ugly truth.
.
You might ask, â??Why would someone do such a thing?â?? â??Are you crazy?!â??
.
Well, yes. I was. And also sad, scared, ashamed.. with anxiety so high I was crawling out of my skin to take it away.
.
Some mouthwash contains more than 20%  alcohol, which is the equivalent of 40-proof liquor. Many also contain hydrogen peroxide and methyl alcohol, which are toxic. Ingesting even a SMALL amount can cause overdose, liver failure, and gastrointestinal damage.
.
But you see, buying mouthwash? I didn't have to face the shame of walking into a liquor with my hat on to cover my swollen, bloodshot eyes and worry if the clerk recognized my face. They know what's going on, as much as we try and hide it or switch up the liquor stores we go to. They know.
.
I didn't WANT to drink. I just wanted the pain, the anxiety, the overwhelm, the shakes to go away. I hated myself for what I was doing, but I didn't see a way out. It scares me today to read of how close I was to not waking up. How much I drank. I didn't it at the time, and quite frankly then, I didn't care if I did.
.
But I decided enoygh was enough. I didnâ??t want to keep digging my rock bottom. I was ready. And this time, I meant it.
.
Iâ??m not sure who needs this right now, but I'm here to tell you that you CAN turn your life around. You can + will feel better. If my body was able to come back from that, I know yours can too. If you treat it well.
.
I'm still here. Because I feel like if I raise my hand and say I've gone though this... I've walked through this or I've done these shameful, embarrassing things... If I talk about my stuff? Then I hope it gives you permission to talk about yours â?
.
You're not alone. And just for tonight...just tonight, you guys... don't drink. I'm rooting for you ð?? {Continued in comments} ð???

Smelling fresh all through the day along with maintaining a heathy personal hygiene is a direct reflection of self care and it is oh so important.
â ?
Today Iâ??m sharing things that I incorporate in my lifestyle and have learnt over time (and am still learning) that help stay fresh for long hauls of time. ð???ð??
â ?
â?¢Invest In good quality and nicely scented soap or shower gel. Some of the brands I  absolutely love are Fiama, Palmolive and The Body Shop.
â ?
â?¢Wash yourself well, like everywhere - You know what I mean. Itâ??s important and a requisite that you quite frankly owe to yourself ladies and gentlemen.
â ?
â?¢Apply perfume right after youâ??ve applied moisturizer. Tried and tested and I can assure you, the perfume stays much longer this way.
â ?
â?¢Use an antiperspirant underarm spray to keep body odour at bay. Nivea Pearl Beauty is â­?ï?
â ?
â?¢Drink celery juice, green tea or pineapple juice which WILL help restore and improve the natural bodily scent. Plus, itâ??s super good for you.
â ?
â?¢Keep tester perfumes or small sized perfumes (Availed at Zara) in your bag. You can pop some on when youâ??re out and about.
â ?
â?¢Invest in a soft scented dry shampoo or/and hair spray - itâ??s an instant pick me up for your hairs texture & smell.
â ?
â?¢Brushing your teeth isnâ??t always enough. Clean your tongue. Use Listerine mouth wash twice a day. Stock up on gums/mints and keep them in your bag.
â ?
â?¢Do not rub your wrists together while applying perfume on your pulse points It causes the scent to turn pungent.
â ?
â?¢Apply a sprinkle of your fave scent on your outfit of the day.
â ?
â?¢Face mists, roll on does (Dove is great) and hand sanitisers are essentials as well.
â ?
â?¢Lastly, let your skin breathe. By that I mean, do not wear any inners, up or down at bedtime.

verbatim_cdownload_content:
* G U M  D I S E A S E *

Do your gums bleed when you brush and floss?

Are your gums swollen and red?

If so, you may have Gingivitis. Gingivitis is the inflammation of your gums due to the accumulation of plaque. Donâ??t worry, gingivitis is reversible! Studies show that if you maintain good oral hygiene your gums will be healthy  again in 21 days.

How do you treat gingivitis?

1ï?â?£ Brush and floss twice daily, morning and night. I personally love Oral-B Glide Prohealth floss. If youâ??re not a fan of flossing then you can opt for a waterpik.

2ï?â?£ Rinse with Listerine twice daily. Try the alcohol-free version which is more gentle.

3ï?â?£ Switch to an electric toothbrush, I love the Philips Sonicare.

4ï?â?£ Make sure you see your hygienist for a cleaning every 6 months!

If Gingivitis is left untreated it can progress into Periodontitis. Periodontitis is more severe because it involves the bone that supports your teeth. Periodontitis can cause bone loss which can the lead to tooth loss.

Great home care and deep cleanings are needed to treat periodontitis. Often times a prescription mouth rinse and/or antibiotic are also used.

Make an appointment with your Dentist so they can provide the best treatment for your needs. Feel free to drop a comment below or message me with any questions. ð?? This picture was taken 7 years ago in Santorini, Greece!! ð??¬ð??·

Just a few TRAVEL ESSENTIALS â??ï?ð??º A proper skincare routine can easily be thrown out the window when traveling, but it doesnâ??t have to be! The key is to PLAN ahead. Make sure all liquids/creams/serums are < 3oz. if they are being brought in your carry on bag. Airplane air is very dehydrating for the skin because it is recycled air that has almost 50% less humidity than what our skin prefers (extremely drying!! â??ï?ð??µ) . Higher altitudes can also cause a duller looking complexion due to decreased blood flow to the skin. Your skin will try to overcompensate for the dryness by producing more oil, so when itâ??s time to land your face could look like a hot, greasy, mess â?? BUT, do not stress! Pack smart ð?§  Below is a list of a few of my on-the-go travel skincare products! âµï?

listerine breath mints because who wants stinky breath?! ð???

Surprisingly, despite my best efforts I could not find a lot of information to support the use of alcohol-based mouth wash over alcohol-free ð??

ALSO, there is some conflicting content on the web about the alcohols anti-bacterial properties. As we know alcohol must be at least 70% to be antiseptic and yet the information about its use in the oral cavity is VERY unclear - mouthwashes may contain up to 27% at the high-endð??

verbatim_cdownload_content:
Ramadan Mubarak everyone!

May this month bring with it blessings to you and your family, peace to your hearts, and all your wishes granted ya rab!

Below are some tips to elevate your daily oral care routine and give you long lasting fresh breath, as well as my favorite things to use every day!: 1) Brush for a minimum of 2 minutes x 2.

I recommend using an electric toothbrush ( Philips Sonicare is > imo). Electric toothbrushes tend to make up for what we usually lack in manually brushing our teeth and I find it helps me get to the areas I would otherwise miss. 
2) Floss. Floss. Floss. (I can not stress this enough) 
Finding this â??My Magic Mudâ?? floss was an accident, but all i can say is, wow. Although idk how i feel about the charcoal fad, this gives me a much deeper clean than i have ever gotten with any other floss. Also a + for xylitol infused (more on that later)

3) CLEAN YOUR TONGUE 
This is a conversation I have with my patients all the time, and it surprises me how many people donâ??t know to do this, but please, for the sake of all things good in the world, clean your tongue! Your tongue harbors a lot (A LOT) of bacteria and so if you donâ??t have one already, please get yourself a tongue scraper (i got mine from the dollar store and it works great) Once you start using it youâ??ll see the difference, guaranteed. 
4) Mouthwash 
Listerine Zero Alcohol. Alcohol in mouthwash tends to dry out your mouth, especially if you use it frequently. (Also nobody got time for dry mouth in Ramadan :) ) Mouthwash is the icing on the cake. 
Hope this helps! Stay safe and enjoy this blessed month with your loved ones <3

Ramadan Mubarak

Love, 
Yasmeen

If you ever go to The Netherlands, youâ??ve got to try oreo Chocâ??o Brownie flavor ð??? I know that as a future dentist, I shouldnâ??t be encouraging anyone to eat sweets, but we all have our weak spotsð???

Unfortunately, so do our teeth, and those weak spots can become cavities if we donâ??t take proper care of themð??³ Such â??weak spotsâ?? can arise from improper brushing and flossing, grinding or other hard motions of the teeth, and low saliva quantity. The importance of flossing daily and how to do so is not usually taught to people by their dentist unless they ask, so donâ??t feel guilty if you donâ??t know what â??properâ?? flossing is! Flossing can help prevent the development of caries (cavities) from weak spots in your teeth. Here are a few easy tips to follow: â??ï? If you canâ??t commit to flossing daily, then floss at least twice a week! You might even find yourself falling into the habit of doing it more often in the future :)
â??ï? Use a fresh piece/section of floss for each tooth. Even if you canâ??t see anything on the floss you previously used, there are still particles on there that you removed from the teeth you already flossed between that you donâ??t want going in the ones you havenâ??t!
â??ï?When flossing, put the floss in between your teeth on an angle- not straight down- and move it into the areas of the gum on each side of the tooth.
â??ï?If your teeth are close together, waxed floss may be easier for you to use because itâ??s design to slip into tight spaces more easily than floss that isnâ??t waxed! listerine floss is a favorite of the dentists I work for â?ºï? The American Dental Association recommends that we floss daily. One complaint that Iâ??ve heard is, â??But my teeth bleed- it hurts!â?? If youâ??re experiencing this issue when you floss, then you either:
A. Donâ??t floss often enough & your gums are bleeding because of plaque buildup
â??ORâ??
B. Floss too roughly

Thus, floss often and be gentle about itâ?? your teeth and gums will thank youâ?ï?

PRODUCT EMPTIES AKA FUTURE TRASH: May-June 23rd. A total of 30 products used up; both in sample and full sizes. I will run through and review some of these items and answer, â??would I buy?â??
The josiemarancosmetics Whipped Argan Oil Body Butter I was excited to try when I picked it up as a sample from sephora. So excited that I grabbed two of them. Each sample contained an â??unscentedâ?? and a â??honeysuckle vanillaâ?? variety. The lotion felt a little greasy, took a little while for my skin to soak up. Both options smelled strongly bitter. I believe itâ??s the aloe juice, which is 2nd on the ingredients list. I know Iâ??m very particular about scents, so it might not bother you. I will not be picking this up in a full size.
The halobeauty Kiwi Seed Booster is the first bottle I have completed. I am contemplating picking up some more to get a better feel for the product. So far, the results are inconclusive because I am in the midst of changing my skin care products. I donâ??t want the testing of new products to interfere with whether I like or dislike this product for me. Itâ??s not fair for me to comment on.
The sephora exfoliating/cleansing wipes are a no go. The exfoliating wipes are way too rough for my sensitive skin and the wipes themselves feel stripping. In a previous empties I talked about taking makeup wipes out of my routines to see if the quality of my skin improves. So far, so good. I switched them out for an oil cleanser to remove makeup. 
The urbandecaycosmetics â??Brow Endowedâ?? primer and color duo samples in â??Taupeâ?? and â??Brunette Bettyâ?? are an absolute disappointment. I was in the market for a new brow product, so I picked up a sample. First impressionâ??the product laid funky. I finessed it a bit and left my house. After some wear timeâ??a couple of hours inâ??my eyebrows looked so awful. The makeup was breaking up throughout my eyebrows. Will not be picking up the product in a full size.
bumbleandbumble â??Hairdresserâ??s Invisible Oilâ?? is nothing special. I used it as an overnight oil treatment. Would not purchase.
listerine mint flossâ??your reminder to floss daily ;) Iâ??ll buy floss again. Definitely like these as opposed to the glide ones.

Good morning, New York!
Did you know that mouthwash can clean floors? If you run out of cleaner, add a capful of mouthwash for every gallon of water and youâ??ll be good to go.ð???
Itâ??s a long story, but to sum it up, Listerine was originally developed to be a surgical antiseptic. However, they realized that surgical antiseptics were only marketable to a small group of professionals. In the hopes of increasing sales, the company began to market Listerine as a floor cleaner â?? as well as a cure for Gonorrhea! So where does mouthwash come in?
By the time the 1920â??s rolled around, they were hungry for a bigger audience. And so began brainstorming issues that everyone faced, that Listerine could cure. By a stroke of genius, they created the medical condition â??chronic halitosisâ?? â?? more commonly known today as bad breath. Apparently back then, bad breath was just â??breathâ??. Seven years later, their revenues skyrocketed past $8 million.

verbatim_cdownload_content:
Tonsil Stones form in the crypts of the palatal tonsils due to trapped debris that calcifies over time. The Tonsils are soft tissue masses similar to lymph nodes that serve as the first line of defense against inhaled and ingested pathogens.

Symptoms of Tonsil Stones, besides huge stones in the back of your throat, include bad breath, sore throat, trouble swallowing, ear pain, ongoing cough and swollen tonsils.

Treatment includes removal of the stones either at home or surgically if the stone is too big. Prevention is key. These can be prevented through practicing good oral hygiene, gargling with salt water, staying hydrated and not smoking.

Did you know that after you brush your teeth, approximately 40% of your tooths surface hasn't been cleaned! That's because our toothbrush cannot reach between our teeth and that's why flossing or iterdental cleaning is so important! Cleaning plaque or bacteria from between your teeth helps to prevent decay, gum disease and bad breath.
There are so many different products that you can use for cleaning between your teeth - floss, flossettes, piksters, water-flossers, just to name a few! .
Make sure you ask your dental professional what you should be using especially if you struggle with conventional floss.
.
I'll be sure to post some tips, tricks and reviews of different iterdental cleaning products in the coming weeks so you can see what products are out there, how to use them and which are most effective.

A reoccurring theme this week clinically is how much patients do not flossð?ð??â??â??ï?. interdental cleaning is a major key (AKA flossing, but there are other means). Dental Pearl: Let's reframe this idea that "FLOSSING needs to be done everyday." EXCUSE ME?...Nope I did not stutter!

Instead of beating a dead horse, let's encourage our patients to clean Interdentally, be it Floss, Flossers, Floss Picks, Go betweens, Water irrigation devices etc. I find that when you make the habit easier to do & give options, patients will be more compliant.

verbatim_cdownload_content:
* T O N G U E  T H R U S T I N G *

Are your teeth starting to flare out?

Are you noticing new spacing between your teeth?

If you answered yes, you could be Tongue thrusting. Tongue thrusting is when you subconsciously push your front teeth with your tongue. Teeth gradually begin to flare out. When this occurs in conjunction with periodontal disease, the results can be very drastic.

Tongue thrusting can have an impact on the aesthetics of your smile and your occlusion (how your teeth come together). In severe cases it can even cause an open bite!

Whatâ??s the right position for your tongue?

Gently rest your tongue on the roof of your mouth about 1/2 inch away from the back of your front teeth. Close your lips and hold your teeth held slightly apart to avoid putting pressure on your teeth.

Stress and anxiety can sometimes cause tongue thrusting. It can also be habitual. 
If your teeth have already been affected:

What can you do to rewind the clock? â?° 
Clear aligners like #ClearCorrect and #Invisalign can return teeth to their original position. This has to be in conjunction with routine cleanings and great home care. Sometimes seeing a speech therapist is also necessary. Talk to your dentist about the best treatment plan for you!

Feel free to drop a comment or questions belowð???ð??. You can also send me a direct message. Hope you found this helpful!

verbatim_cdownload_content:
A dry mouth is likely to cause bad breath. Keep that in mind. 
So how do you prevent bad breath?

1. Back to basics: Review your oral hygiene. 
A. Brush your teeth AND YOUR TONGUE twice a day. You may add rinsing with an antibacterial mouthwash. If you have any dentures, remove them and clean them thoroughly every night. 
B. Change your toothbrush every 2-3months. 
2. Stay hydrated. Drink water regularly. Also, chewing gum containing mint can stimulate saliva production which keeps the mouth moist to prevent bad odor 
3. Keep a log of the foods that you eat in case you're suspecting that it is the cause of your bad breath. Show the log to your dentist and they may be able to help you. 
4. Stop smoking 
5. Visit your dentist and tell them your big secret and let them assess you. It may be due to an underlying condition. They will be able to give you appropriate medication.

verbatim_cdownload_content:
Do you use mouthwash? Mouthwash is helpful only IN ADDITION to brushing and flossing. You see, brushing and flossing are mechanical actions - they actually rub against the teeth to remove debris, like bacteria and food. Mouthwash is just swished around, so it does NOT remove debris from your teeth. In order for mouthwash to work best, it is imperative that you floss and brush your teeth first to remove the debris. The mouthwash can then do what it is supposed to do.

So what do you want your mouthwash to do? * Cavity Protection: look for mouthwashes that contain Fluoride - an ingredient that fights tooth decay and strengthens enamel
* Fight Bad Breath and Inflamed Gums: most mouthwashes simply mask bad breath. Look for ingredients like essential oils (menthol, eucalyptus, and thymol), Cetylpyridinium chloride, chlorine dioxide, and alcohol, which kill bacteria that contribute to bad breath and gum disease.
* Fight Periodontal Disease: periodontitis is a more serious form of gum disease. Prescription mouthwashes containing ingredients like chlorhexidine are helpful in treating periodontal disease. * Treat Dry Mouth: if you suffer from dry mouth, youâ??ll want to avoid mouthwashes that contain alcohol, as alcohol will further dry out your mouth. People with dry mouth are more prone to decay, so it is important to use a mouthwash containing fluoride. Ingredients like xylitol can help kill bacteria and increase saliva. * Whitening: ingredients like carbide peroxide and hydrogen peroxide can help whiten your teeth, although mouthwashes are not very effective in whitening your teeth. Watch out for stannous fluoride, which can cause staining. We find that Crest ProHealth Mouthwash tends to cause staining in our patients.

So, make sure you check the ingredients in order to find a mouthwash that is right for your needs! 
I always recommend to check the mouthwash label for the ADA Seal of Acceptance. It means that itâ??s been tested for effectiveness.

And, always consult your dentist! If you are prone to bad breath, cavities, gum disease, etc, you should be examined for underlying conditions and better treatment options!

Feel free to ask me anything!

verbatim_cdownload_content:
Will Mouthwash Like Listerine, Scope, or Peridex Kill Coronavirus or Covid-19?

The answer is NO. At this point, there is no evidence that mouthwashes protect you from Coronavirus. 
However, it appears from a recent study, that 1% hydrogen peroxide will reduce the salivary load of the coronavirus. The American Dental Association is recommending dentists have patients rinse with 1% hydrogen peroxide for 1 minute before we start any dental procedure on them. It is sold usually as 3% hydrogen peroxide. It can be diluted down by adding water. So for example add 5ml of water to 5ml of 3% hydrogen peroxide and mix to get it to half strength or 1.5%. Thus at home it's advisable to disinfect your toothbrush with hydrogen peroxide; even soak your mouthguard and retainers in it for 5-10 minutes. You can even rinse your mouth with 1.5% hydrogen peroxide for 60 seconds.

A pre dental procedural mouthrinse would be most useful in cases when rubber dam cannot be used.

Dr. Rico D. Short 
Board Certified Endodontist / Author / Speaker 
Apex Endodontics P.C / Atlanta  #covid19 #dentistry # #staysafe #drricoshort #coronoavirus #oralhealth #ada

When I ask my patients if they floss or not I usually get 3 types of answers.. Some patients would laugh and say â??noâ?? very simple and I love it!! I always say, â??well thank you for being honest!!â?? Some other patients (and this is very common!) say â??Not as much as I shouldâ?? this also means noâ?ºï?And those who floss, I donâ??t ask, I just say looks like you are flossing to get the biggest smile of the day in responseð???
We all have heard that we need to brush and floss our teeth, but why do we really need to?? When I ask patients this question they usually say â?? to not get cavitiesâ??... I will get into more details about that on a later post, but lets stick with that for now.. â? ï?ARTISTS ATWORKâ? ï?
Whatâ??s your favourite toothpaste and what do you recommend? 
Always look at the ingredients to help guide you to make an informed decision on what to recommend.
- if there is sodium bicarbonate or charcoal, the toothpaste is 
aimed to whiten teeth.
- if there is chorexedine or triclosan, it is for gum Health. - if there is potassium nitrate or Argenine, the toothpaste aims to desensitise your teeth and therefore reduce sensitivity. - be aware that the majority of toothpastes have sodium lauryl sulphate in them to create that â??foamyâ?? effect. Many patients (including the little one!) are allergic to this. If so, recommend sensodyne pronamel which is SLS free. - Last but definitely not least, make sure the toothpaste you have or recommend has some type of fluoride in it, preferably over 1300ppm. This can come as sodium fluoride, potassium fluoride, stannuous fluoride ... the list goes on!

DIABETES AND DENTAL CARE

To help prevent damage to your teeth and gums, take diabetes and dental care seriously:

Make a commitment to manage your diabetes. Monitor your blood sugar level, and follow your doctor's instructions for keeping your blood sugar level within your target range. The better you control your blood sugars, the less likely you are to develop gingivitis and other dental problems.

Brush your teeth at least twice a day. Brush in the morning, at night and, ideally, after meals and snacks. Use a soft-bristled toothbrush and toothpaste that contains fluoride. Avoid vigorous or harsh scrubbing, which can irritate your gums.

Consider using an electric toothbrush, especially if you have arthritis or other problems that make it difficult to brush well. Get a new toothbrush at least every three months.

Floss your teeth at least once a day. Flossing helps remove plaque between your teeth and under your gumline. If you have trouble getting dental floss through your teeth, use the waxed variety. If it's hard to manipulate the floss, use a floss holder.

Schedule regular dental visits. Visit your dentist at least twice a year for professional cleanings, X-rays and checkups.

Make sure your dentist knows you have diabetes. Every time you visit your dentist, remind him or her that you have diabetes. Make sure your dentist has contact information for your doctor who helps you manage your diabetes.

Look for early signs of gum disease. Report any signs of gum disease â?? including redness, swelling and bleeding gums â?? to your dentist. Also mention any other signs and symptoms, such as dry mouth, loose teeth or mouth pain.

Don't smoke. Smoking increases the risk of serious diabetes complications, including gum disease and ultimately, loss of your teeth.

Managing diabetes is a lifelong commitment, and that includes proper dental care. Your efforts will be rewarded with a lifetime of healthy teeth and gums.

Emergency Dental Hacks: #1

Sensitivity toothpastes (like sensodyne or crest Pro-Health Sensitivity) or high-fluoride rinses (like ACT or listerine Total Care) are specially formulated to help protect sensitive areas of teeth. If you have an exposed area at the gum line, a lost filling or a broken tooth, then apply a generous amount of the toothpaste and let it sit for as long as possible (even overnight) or rinse 2-3 times daily. This will allow the anti-sensitivity medication to be absorbed - it may take several applications over several days but it could make a big difference!

Knockout that bacteria for healthier gums

Did you know that over 90% of the worldâ??s population have some degree of gingivitis? How about that 75% of adults in the US have gingivitis? Or that nearly 2 in 3 adults with gingivitis are unaware they suffer from gum disease?

Beginning stages of gum disease include gingivitis which can show up in signs such as redness, bleeding, and inflammation of the gums. The good news is that gingivitis is reversible if treated before bone loss occurs.

As a dental hygienist most of my work is focused on preventing, treating, and educating on gum disease. Itâ??s so important to me that patients know the foundation of their teeth (gums, bone) is as important as having a good looking smile for both their oral and overall health.

Listerine Gum Therapy is made with a combination of 4 essential oils, zinc chloride, and other ingredients to help knockout bacteria that can cause gingivitis.

Iâ??ll admit Iâ??m not a regular user of Listerine or any other mouth rinses. But I do think rinses have a place in a good oral care routine. Depending on my patientâ??s needs I recommend different rinses, although I usually tell them I want to see them brush and clean in between their teeth regularly before adding an extra step.

Have you tried Listerine Gum Therapy? What are your thoughts on mouth rinses? What are some brands you recommend?

Bringing the biggest life hack today ð???ð??? thayersnatural witch hazel toner is a must have. It is available at every single drug store, and it has a massive cult following. Toners meant to help remove any excess makeup or dirt after cleansers and before moisturizers. They also correct skinâ??s ph balance and help prevent breakout. Typically witch hazel toners normally have a strong smell and a burning feeling. Thayerâ??s does not feel this way, it is great for all skin types. 
BUT the life hack might not be good for all skin types. I have had multiple people recommend mixing Blue listerine (has to be the one with alcohol and antiseptic on the label) with whatever toner you would normally use. The antiseptic properties kill bacteria that cause breakouts. At first I did not think this would be a good idea to put on my skin, because of the alcohol content which dries everything out. So at first I just used it on breakouts, and they would be dried out by the morning if I applied it at night. Eventually I started soaking a cotton pad in the Thayerâ??s toner then adding around four-six drops of listerine and wiping my entire face and neck area with the cotton pad. Itâ??s refreshing for my skin, because of the minty-ness of the listerine. I do this both morning and night. Sometimes I increase the listerine amount if I have been gardening or swimming or anything that increases the likelihood of me having more bacteria on my skin

.

verbatim_cdownload_content:
Two years ago today I made the choice to use one of the toughest days of my life as one of the my greatest opportunities for growth.
â??
April 6, 2017, I found myself starring at oncoming traffic as I slid down the street hanging from upside down in the truck you see above.  It wasnâ??t my finest hour, and I still face the repercussions of that choice to this day.  However, on April 7, 2017 nothing would be the same, and my life changed for the better.
â??
On this day, April 7, I made the decision to do ONE THING to make myself a better version of me than I was the day before.  It started with flossing my teeth.  It sounds overly simple, not hard to do and almost trivial when I think about it now, but it was the ONE THING I knew I could do on that day to get me closer to the man I knew I could be.  Two years later, I hardly recognize myself.
â??
What started with flossing has led me to the daily habits you see on the bottom right.  Each one of those things I do for myself EVERYDAY in order to be the best version of myself the world has ever seen.  Who would have thought that one small task could lead to so much growth and expansion.
â??
I have so much to be grateful for and so many people to thank for being there for me during this journey.  I know i havenâ??t always made it easy on myself or those around me, and I thank all those who have stood by my side.
â??
Today we all have the chance to be better than we were yesterday.  We wonâ??t always be perfect at it, and thatâ??s OK.  Please donâ??t ever forget how one small thing can lead to bigger and better.  If I can do it so can you.
â??
If you life isnâ??t good, know that youâ??re not alone and it will get better.  If you life is good but not great, know that what youâ??re after is within your reach.  If your life is great, keep doing the daily work to stay there.
â??
I love, honor and appreciate all those fighting the daily war to be the best version of you the world has ever seen.
â??

Gay twitter has torn apart pride campaigns, criticizing them for being lazy, opportunistic, overly centered on the pride flag, or insensitive.
